1 SECTION 1. IC 2-5-56.8 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 56.8. Deed Fraud Task Force
5 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "task force" refers to the deed
6 fraud task force established by section 2 of this chapter.
7 Sec. 2. The deed fraud task force is established.
8 Sec. 3. (a) The task force consists of the following thirteen (13)
9 members:
10 (1) A member of the house of representatives who is
11 appointed to the task force by the speaker of the house of
12 representatives.
13 (2) A member of the senate who is appointed to the task force
14 by the president pro tempore of the senate.
15 (3) A member of the house of representatives who is
16 appointed to the task force by the minority leader of the house
17 of representatives.
2026 IN 253—LS 7060/DI 154

2
1 (4) A member of the senate who is appointed to the task force
2 by the minority leader of the senate.
3 (5) The chief justice of the supreme court or a designee of the
4 chief justice.
5 (6) The attorney general or the attorney general's designee.
6 (7) A representative from the state police department.
7 (8) The treasurer of state or the treasurer of state's designee.
8 (9) The following members who are appointed to the task
9 force by the governor:
10 (A) A notary public (as defined in IC 33-42-0.5-20).
11 (B) A title insurance agent (as defined in IC 35-43-9-4).
12 (C) A county recorder.
13 (D) A real estate broker licensed under IC 25-34.1.
14 (E) A representative from a consumer advocacy group that
15 represents the interests of consumers who are fifty (50)
16 years of age or older.
17 (b) The members appointed under subsection (a)(1) and (a)(2)
18 shall serve as co-chairs.
19 (c) A member appointed under subsection (a)(9) may not be a
20 member of the general assembly.
21 (d) A member serves at the will of the member's appointing
22 authority. If a vacancy occurs in the task force, the appointing
23 authority who appointed the member whose position is vacant shall
24 appoint an individual to fill the vacancy.
25 (e) An individual appointed to fill a vacancy must meet the
26 qualifications of the vacancy.
27 (f) An individual appointed to fill a vacancy serves for the
28 remainder of the term of the member the individual is appointed
29 to succeed.
30 Sec. 4. (a) Seven (7) members of the task force constitute a
31 quorum.
32 (b) The affirmative vote of at least a majority of the members at
33 a meeting at which a quorum is present is necessary for the task
34 force to take official action other than to meet and take testimony.
35 (c) The task force shall meet at the call of the co-chairs.
36 Sec. 5. All meetings of the task force are open to the public in
37 accordance with and subject to IC 5-14-1.5. All records of the task
38 force are subject to the requirements of IC 5-14-3.
39 Sec. 6. The task force shall:
40 (1) assess the extent of deed fraud in Indiana; and
41 (2) consider approaches to reduce deed fraud in Indiana.
42 Sec. 7. The task force shall:
2026 IN 253—LS 7060/DI 154

3
1 (1) develop recommendations for the legislative council
2 concerning the topics set forth in section 6 of this chapter;
3 (2) issue a report setting forth the recommendations
4 developed under subdivision (1); and
5 (3) not later than June 30, 2027, submit the report to the
6 legislative council in an electronic format under IC 5-14-6.
7 Sec. 8. The legislative services agency shall provide staff support
8 to the task force.
9 Sec. 9. (a) Each legislative member and each lay member of the
10 task force is entitled to receive the same per diem, mileage, and
11 travel allowances paid to individuals serving as legislative and lay
12 members, respectively, on an interim study committee established
13 by the legislative council.
14 (b) A member of the task force who is a state employee is not
15 entitled to a per diem. However, the member is entitled to receive
16 the same travel allowances paid to members of the task force
17 described in subsection (a).
18 Sec. 10. The task force's expenses, including the payment of per
19 diem and reimbursements under section 9 of this chapter, are
20 payable from amounts appropriated to the legislative council.
21 Sec. 11. This chapter expires July 1, 2027.
22 SECTION 2. IC 32-21-2-17 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
23 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
24 1, 2026]: Sec. 17. (a) As used in this section:
25 (1) "Suspicious instrument" means an instrument (as defined
26 in section 1.5 of this chapter) for which the county recorder
27 has found any of the following:
28 (A) The name of a notarial officer or notary public who
29 has purported to acknowledge or verify the instrument
30 does not match official records.
31 (B) The instrument purports not to be subject to the laws
32 of the United States or Indiana.
33 (C) The instrument does not conform to the recording
34 standards enacted by the general assembly.
35 (D) The instrument has not been submitted for recording
36 by a trusted submitter or an authorized representative of
37 a trusted submitter and the instrument is materially false,
38 fictitious, or fraudulent.
39 (2) "Title insurance agent" means a person who holds a
40 limited lines producer's license issued under
41 IC 27-1-15.6-18(3) and disburses funds from a title insurance
42 escrow account to a party in connection with a real property
2026 IN 253—LS 7060/DI 154

4
1 transaction.
2 (3) "Trusted submitter" means:
3 (A) a title insurance agent;
4 (B) a title company;
5 (C) an escrow company;
6 (D) an attorney licensed to practice law in Indiana; and
7 (E) a financial institution (as defined in IC 28-1-1-3(1)).
8 (b) A county recorder may:
9 (1) refuse to record a suspicious instrument, unless a court of
10 competent jurisdiction finds that the county recorder's
11 finding that the instrument is a suspicious instrument is
12 erroneous;
13 (2) report a suspicious instrument to the appropriate law
14 enforcement agency; or
15 (3) notify a notarial officer or notary public who has
16 purported to acknowledge or prove a suspicious instrument
17 of the reason for the county recorder's finding that the
18 instrument is a suspicious instrument.
19 (c) A person may bring an action seeking a declaratory
20 judgment or injunctive relief against a county recorder for the
21 county recorder's refusal to record an instrument under this
22 section if the person believes that the county recorder erroneously
23 determined that the instrument is a suspicious instrument. A
24 county recorder is not liable for damages in an action brought
25 under this subsection.
26 SECTION 3. IC 32-21-2.2 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
27 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
28 JULY 1, 2026]:
29 Chapter 2.2. Property Alert Notification System
30 Sec. 1. Not later than January 1, 2027, each county recorder in
31 Indiana shall establish a property alert notification system that
32 allows a person to enroll the person's real property in the system.
33 Sec. 2. A property alert notification system required to be
34 established under this chapter shall do the following:
35 (1) Notify a person that enrolls the person's real property in
36 a property alert notification system required to be established
37 under this chapter of the recording of any instrument (as
38 defined in IC 32-21-2-1.5) that affects or may affect the
39 person's real property.
40 (2) In the notification described in subdivision (1), identify the
41 nature of the instrument (as defined in IC 32-21-2-1.5),
42 identify the real property by address or tax identification
2026 IN 253—LS 7060/DI 154

5
1 number, and provide the recording information of the
2 instrument (as defined in IC 32-21-2-1.5).
3 (3) Allow a person that enrolls the person's real property in a
4 property alert notification system required to be established
5 under this chapter to elect to receive the notification
6 described in subdivision (1) by mail, electronic mail, text
7 message, or telephone call.
8 Sec. 3. A charge may not be assessed to a person for enrolling
9 the person's real property in a property alert notification system
10 required to be established under this chapter.
11 Sec. 4. A county recorder may, through any medium, provide
12 property owners with:
13 (1) educational information on deed fraud; and
14 (2) information about the property alert notification system
15 that the county recorder is required to establish under this
16 chapter.
17 Sec. 5. (a) A county recorder is not liable for a violation of this
18 chapter.
19 (b) This section does not create a cause of action against a
20 county recorder regarding the establishment, maintenance, or
21 operation of a property alert notification system required to be
22 established under this chapter.
23 SECTION 4. IC 32-21-2.3 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
