20 SECTION 5. IC 33-42-9-4, AS AMENDED BY P.L.59-2018,
21 SECTION 45, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
22 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) A notarial officer has personal knowledge
23 of an individual's identity if the:
24 (1) individual is personally known to the notarial officer; or
25 (2) notarial officer has transacted sufficient, prior business with
26 the individual to know the individual's identity.
27 (b) If a notarial officer does not have personal knowledge of an
28 individual's identity, the notarial officer may authenticate the identity
29 of the individual through one (1) of the following means:
30 (1) An inspection of any of the following that, if expired, has not
31 been expired for more than three (3) years:
32 (A) The individual's passport.
33 (B) The individual's driver's license.
34 (C) The individual's government issued identification card.
35 (D) A credential that:
36 (i) is not described in clauses (A) through (C);
37 (ii) is government issued; and
38 (iii) contains a photograph of the individual.
39 (2) A verification on an oath or affirmation by a credible witness
40 who:
41 (A) personally:
42 (i) appears before the notarial officer; and
2026 IN 253—LS 7060/DI 154

7
1 (ii) is personally known by the notarial officer; or
2 (B) is identified to the notarial officer by a credential
3 described in subdivision (1).
4 (c) A notarial officer may require an individual to provide additional
5 identification or information before performing a notarial act,
6 including providing sufficient information to conduct identity
7 proofing.
8 SECTION 6. IC 33-42-9-5, AS ADDED BY P.L.128-2017,
9 SECTION 18, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
10 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 5. (a) A notarial officer may refuse to perform a
11 notarial act if the notarial officer is not satisfied that:
12 (1) the individual executing the record is competent; or
13 (2) the individual's execution of the record is being done
14 knowingly or voluntarily; or
15 (3) the individual executing the record has provided sufficient
16 information to conduct identity proofing under section 4(c) of
17 this chapter.
18 (b) A notarial officer may refuse to perform a notarial act unless the
19 refusal is prohibited by law.
